Dynamic model of Otbot

This live script develops the dynamic model of Otbot and the solution to its forward and inverse dynamics problems.

2. Computation of the mass matrix

Recall that the robot configuration is given by
To find the mass matrix we first write the kinetic energy T of the robot as a function of and and then express it as:
The robot has four bodies: the main body of the chassis, the left wheel, the right wheel, and the platform. We have to compute the translational and rotational kinetic energies of all bodies, and add them all to obtain T:
% Chassis angle theta, and its derivative, in terms of qdot
theta = alpha - varphi_p;
theta_dot= alpha_dot - varphi_dot_p;
% Translational kinetic energies
T_tra_b = kin_en_trans(x_G, y_G, m_b, x_dot, y_dot, theta, theta_dot); % Main chassis body
T_tra_r = kin_en_trans(-l_1, -l_2, m_w, x_dot, y_dot, theta, theta_dot); % Right wheel
T_tra_l = kin_en_trans(-l_1, l_2, m_w, x_dot, y_dot, theta, theta_dot); % Left wheel
T_tra_p = kin_en_trans(x_F, y_F, m_p, x_dot, y_dot, alpha, alpha_dot); % Platform
% Rotational kinetic energies
T_rot_b = 1/2 * I_b * (theta_dot)^2; % Main chassis body
T_rot_r = 1/2 * I_a * (varphi_dot_r)^2 + 1/2 * I_t * (theta_dot)^2; % Right wheel
T_rot_l = 1/2 * I_a * (varphi_dot_l)^2 + 1/2 * I_t * (theta_dot)^2; % Left wheel
T_rot_p = 1/2 * I_p * (alpha_dot)^2; % Platform
% Total kinetic energy
T = T_tra_b + T_tra_p + T_tra_r + T_tra_l + ...
T_rot_b + T_rot_p + T_rot_r + T_rot_l;
% Display the results
display(T_tra_b); display(T_tra_p); display(T_tra_r); display(T_tra_l);

3. Computation of the Coriolis matrix

Recall that the element of is given by the following formula (see Murray, Sastry, Lee)
,
which in Matlab can be implemented as follows:
qvec = [x y alpha varphi_r varphi_l varphi_p].';
qdotvec = [x_dot y_dot alpha_dot varphi_dot_r varphi_dot_l varphi_dot_p].';
nq = length(qvec);
Cmat = sym(zeros(nq,nq));
for i=1:nq
for j=1:nq
for k=1:nq
Cmat(i,j) = Cmat(i,j) + qdotvec(k) * 0.5 * ( ...
diff(Mmat(i,j),qvec(k)) + ...
diff(Mmat(i,k),qvec(j)) - ...
diff(Mmat(k,j),qvec(i)) );
end
end
end

Appendix 1: Symbolic inverse of the abstract mass matrix

Symbolic expressions of our mass matrix might be useful to later compute analytic gradients and Hessians of our dynamic equations. For later use, we here find the symbolic inverse of an abstract matrix with the same sparsity pattern as :
% Symbolic variable definitions
syms sigma_11 sigma_22 sigma_33 sigma_44 sigma_55 sigma_66 sigma_13 sigma_23 sigma_16 sigma_26 sigma_36
tic
% Abstract mass matrix
Ma = [
sigma_11 0 sigma_13 0 0 sigma_16;
0 sigma_22 sigma_23 0 0 sigma_26;
sigma_13 sigma_23 sigma_33 0 0 sigma_36;
0 0 0 sigma_44 0 0;
0 0 0 0 sigma_55 0;
sigma_16 sigma_26 sigma_36 0 0 sigma_66
]
Ma = 
% Compute the adjoint and the determinant separately, to get smaller formulas
Adjoint_of_Ma = adjoint(Ma);
Determinant_of_Ma = det(Ma);

Appendix 2: Function kin_en_trans

This function computes the kinetic energy of a point P of a body, of mass m, in terms of the body pose and twist.
The following notation is used:
  • = Local coordinates of P in the body-fixed frame
  • m = mass of P
  • = Absolute coordinates of the origin of the body-fixed frame
  • θ = absolute angle of the body
Note: This function can be used to compute the translational kinetic energy: just let P be the c.o.m. of the body, and m be the total mass of the body.
function T = kin_en_trans(a,b,m,xdot,ydot,theta,thetadot)
c = cos(theta);
s = sin(theta);
A = [1, 0, -c*b - s*a;
0, 1, c*a - s*b;
0, 0, 1 ];
Mp = [m, 0, 0; 0, m, 0; 0, 0, 0];
M = simplify(transpose(A) * Mp * A);
w = [xdot;ydot;thetadot];
T = expand(1/2 * transpose(w) * M * w,'ArithmeticOnly',true);
end
